'''Marla Spivak''' (born 1955) is an American [[entomologist]], and Distinguished McKnight University Professor at the [[University of Minnesota]] specializing in [[apiculture]] and social insects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.entomology.umn.edu/People/GradFaculty/Spivak/ |title=Marla Spivak : Department of Entomology : College of Food, Agricultural and Natural Resource Sciences : University of Minnesota |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140825090039/http://www.entomology.umn.edu/People/GradFaculty/Spivak/ |archive-date=2014-08-25 |df= }}</ref>

==Career and Research Contributions==
Spivak graduated with a B.A. from [[Humboldt State University]] and a Ph.D. from the [[University of Kansas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.macfound.org/fellows/43/|title=Marla Spivak — MacArthur Foundation|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.entomology.umn.edu/faculty-staff/marla-spivak|title=Marla Spivak|last=dalyx224|date=2014-08-11|website=Department of Entomology|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>
She is particularly well known for her work breeding lines of honey bees that detect and quickly remove diseased larvae and pupae, which is called hygienic behavior.<ref name="Spivak et al 2008">{{cite web|url=http://www.beelab.umn.edu/prod/groups/cfans/@pub/@cfans/@bees/documents/asset/cfans_asset_317498.pdf|title=The Future of the MN Hygienic Stock of Bees is in Good Hands!|last=Spivak|first=Marla|date=December 2008|work=[[American Bee Journal]]|accessdate=August 8, 2015}}</ref> She was instrumental in setting up the first bee Tech-Transfer Team in the United States,<ref name="McNeil 2010">{{cite web|url=https://www.beelab.umn.edu/sites/beelab.umn.edu/files/back-on-feet.pdf|title=Getting bees back on their own six feet|last=McNeil|first=M.E.A.|date=September 2010|work=[[American Bee Journal]]|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name="Lee 2011- Bee Informed Partnership Blog">{{cite web|url=https://beeinformed.org/2011/06/07/origins/|title=Origins|last=Lee|first=Katie|date=June 2011|work=[[Bee Informed Partnership Blog]]|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref> which continues to help honey bee queen breeders select for disease resistance traits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beeinformed.org/programs/tech-teams/|title=Tech Teams   - Bee Informed Partnership|publisher=}}</ref> More recently, she has begun studying the role of resins, which bees collect and mix with wax to make [[propolis]] coatings on the inside of their hives, as an example of honey bee [[social immunity]].<ref name="Spivak 2013">{{cite web|url=http://www.beelab.umn.edu/prod/groups/cfans/@pub/@cfans/@bees/documents/article/cfans_article_435997.pdf|title=The Benefits of Propolis|last=Spivak|first=Marla|date=March 2013|work=Bee Craft Magazine|accessdate=August 8, 2015}}</ref> Her lab also studies the effect of the surrounding landscape on the health and nutrition of both honey bees and native bees.<ref name="Miller 2013">{{cite web|url=http://www.mprnews.org/story/2013/04/01/daily-circuit-saving-the-bees|title=With hives in sharp decline, expert calls for bee-friendly flowers|last=Miller|first=Kerri|date=April 1, 2013|work=[[MPR News]]|accessdate=August 8, 2015}}</ref>

==Awards==
She was awarded a [[MacArthur Fellowship]] grant in 2010 for her work with [[honey bees]].<ref name="Ross">{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/stpaul/103973263.html|title=Buzz about U professor is 'genius’|last=Ross|first=Jenna|date=September 28, 2010|work=[[Star Tribune]]|accessdate=April 25, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Horn2011">{{cite book|last=Horn|first=Tammy|title=Beeconomy: What Women and Bees Can Teach Us about Local Trade and the Global Market|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8kUWyjIVzwUC&pg=PT170|date=November 1, 2011|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=9780813134369|pages=170}}</ref> After receiving the MacArthur grant, she started an organization called the [https://www.beelab.umn.edu/bee-squad Bee Squad], which works to help beekeepers and people in the Twin Cities community improve the health of bee pollinators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beelab.umn.edu/bee-squad|title=Bee Squad|last=hvander|date=2015-01-27|website=Bee Lab|language=en|access-date=2019-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://beelab.umn.edu/BeeSquad/ |title=Bee Squad : Bee Lab : Department of Entomology : University of Minnesota |publisher=Regents of the University of Minnesota |year=2014 |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130414013345/http://beelab.umn.edu/BeeSquad/ |archive-date=2013-04-14 |df= }}</ref> In 2015, she won the Distinguished Service Award from the Minnesota AgriGrowth Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://agrigrowth.org/membership/distinguished-service-award/|title=Distinguished Service Award|publisher=AgriGrowth|date=2016}}</ref> In 2016, she won the Siehl Prize for Excellence in Agriculture (category: Knowledge) for her many contributions to understanding bee biology and threats to bee health<ref>{{cite web|url=http://discover.umn.edu/news/food-agriculture/siehl-prize-excellence-agriculture-announces-2016-laureates/|title=Siehl Prize for Excellence in Agriculture announces 2016 laureates|first=|last=Anonymous|date=16 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref> and a [[Women of Discovery Award]] from Wings Worldquest, honoring her pioneering work promoting bee health and conservation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wingsworldquest.org/2016-womenofdiscovery-gala/ |title=2016 Women of Discovery Awards |publisher=WINGS WorldQuest |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901204504/http://www.wingsworldquest.org/2016-womenofdiscovery-gala |archive-date=2016-09-01 |df= }}</ref>
Spivak was elected a Fellow of the [[Entomological Society of America]] in 2017.<ref>http://entsoc.org/ten-entomologists-join-ranks-fellows-entomological-society-america</ref>

